snippet.textDisplay:
funny how some people think 3:2 is a walk in the park. 5:27
I think many people actually believe it is a win-win and you don't lose anything only gaining vertical wideness.
got a shitload of these 7mm unibody Book tablets https://i.imgur.com/H8ijtSR.jpg
and measured a 13.3" +500nits 3200x1800 277PPI tablet panel from Porsche vs Surface Book2 3000x2000 - 266PPI with 13.5" and even though the SB2 with 3:2 was 0.2" inches bigger with 13.5" vs 13.3" i lost a 1cm in horizontal while gaining 2.5cm in vertical and no doubt that 1cm in horizontal view was noticeable when watching media.
The 13.5" was ideal when drawing etc with bigger high screen real-estate..but media and youtube etc that 1cm on the 13.3" really did make quite a noticeable difference. https://i.imgur.com/ugPIAMM.jpg
In some circumstances 3:2 ideal while in others not so much..
and no the device ain't to thin for USB A port ... aint the Surface X like + 7mm? (// yep 7.3mm) so around the same as Surface Book2 at 7½mm.. when they can have a surface connect port, you can bet they would also have thickness for a USB A port.. perhaps they don't have room, but lack of thickness aint the sinner ..(don't eat that excuse sucking-cloth from Microsoft 6:00 )

snippet.textDisplay:
No, the power of arm is not a "smaller" instructions set.
The power of arm comes from the instructions sets' features that allowed setting priority to different process and instructions.
This allows the arm CPU to only run the most mission critical of functions under different conditions. It even allows it to shut off parts of the CPU if it is deemed unnecessary.
This saves a lot of energy. Especially while idling. Energy saving is extremely important to all mobile devices because of their really limited charge capacity.

snippet.textDisplay:
@4:20
"and even then performance will likely be worse than 32bit emulated x86 apps".

If anything emulation of x86-64bit apps would perform better? Since a lot of the reasoning behind x86-64 was to bring RISC like features to x86 such as more general purpose registers, a feature which the ARM instruction set uses heavily for performance. The code generated when building x86-64 rather than x86 produces a lot fewer stack push and pop operations as more values can be held in general purpose registers for longer, and even function parameters can be passed via the general purpose registers. Assuming a JIT recompiler emulator is used, a must for performance when emulating different architectures, this would potentially allow x86-64 to produce more efficient to execute ARM code since fewer stack operations will occur and more ARM registers can be used instead. If there is a significant performance regression it would be ARM32 vs ARM64 or maybe due to SSE2 vector instruction usage rather than x86-64 itself.

snippet.textDisplay: Reduced instruction sets are also suitable for powerhouse tasks, its just that most programs right now are written for complex instruction sets. The reason we use complex instruction sets was because computers did not have enough storage to hold both the program and all the data it needed. Most processors convert complex instruction sets to reduced ones on the fly anyway. Reduced instruction sets are better for pipelining, making the possibility for higher IPCs possible

snippet.textDisplay: So I'm wondering why someone would run this vs a Macbook which is proven stable, less expensive (by far) for the same processing, graphics, storage (etc...) and will scale much better. The only thing I can see about this is MS trying to catch up to the Mac on battery life, but failing on every other front. The one edge MS has is running high end machines that are prohibitively expensive for Macs and the fact said machines will run software Macs won't. This does neither of those so I'm left wondering what the marketable case is for this product. As a side note, I never thought I'd see the day that Apple beat MS on hardware parity cost. If I could short sell a product, this would definitely be it.
